54 ON OLD AGE

11 14 cuiusque: referring to the senes implied in the abstract senectus above. ,

11 15 Quid: ‘how is it with?' see note on 22, p. 9, l. 23,—addiscunt: ‘leam something new! He has spoken of those who continue in old age the pursuits they carried on when young, tale scilicet, ete., but some even go so far as to begin new pursuits.

11 17 et ego feci = et ut egoseci.

11 18 litteras Graecas: ‘ Greek literature'; cf. Cic. Ac. Pr. 2, 5: cum Graecas litteras M. Catonem in senectute didicisse acceperim. See note on 3, p. 2, l. 12. — sic avide: both these words modify arripui, and sic is explained by quasi. Cf. 12, p. 6, 1. 8, ita . . . quasi.

11 19 ut . . . essent: purpose clause— Cato’s reason for reading Greek.

11 21 Quod: i.e. acquiring new knowledge in old age.

11 22 vellen: potential suij. referring to the past, ‘ I should have wished,' etc. 5447, 1; 442, b; G. 2583 H. 556. —disoebant: the fact that Socrates learned to play the lyre in old age gave Cato the desire to do the same, while the ancient Romans themselves afforded precedents suffi- cient to justify him and save his sels-respect. The clause discebant . . . antiqui seems like an after-thought on the part of Cicero, on realizing that Cato would hardly have taken Socrates as a model.

11 23 fidibus: abl. of means (se. canere), but tr. ‘leam the lyre.' —- certe: i.e. if not in music, at any rate in literature.

11 24 desidero: ‘feel the want of!

11 25 locus: in its technical rhetorical sense locus may mean (1) an argument of a general nature, such as may be used in various specific cases (locus communis), or (2) the headings under which certain arguments are grouped; i.e. the place where they are to be found. Here it has the latter meaning, recalling the four general headings in the indictment against old age (ι 5), among which diminution of strength was the second.

11 27 Quod est . . . agere pro viribus: i.e. use the strength you have, but proportion your activity to this strength, so as not to feel aggrieved, as Milo did, if you cannot carry this activity beyond a certain point.

11 28 vox: ‘words.’—contemptior: more despicable.’

12 1 At: those athletes’ muscles are strong, ‘but these muscles of mine,' etc.

12 3 nugator: ‘fool.'

ν 12 4 Nihil . . . tale: supply some such verb as dicebant.

12 6 iura . . . praescribebantur: ‘ laws were interpreted’ See note on 22, p. 9, l. 23, iuris consulti.
